Abstract 

Lung disease prediction using artificial intelligence (AI) has emerged as a powerful approach to improving early diagnosis and patient management. By analyzing medical data such as chest X-rays, CT scans, lung sounds, and clinical records, AI models can identify subtle patterns that may not be easily detected through traditional diagnostic methods. This enables the early detection of conditions such as pneumonia, tuberculosis, asthma, COPD, and lung cancer. The integration of machine learning and deep learning techniques enhances predictive accuracy, supports clinical decision-making, and reduces diagnostic delays. Furthermore, AI-driven systems can assist in monitoring disease progression and personalizing treatment strategies based on individual patient profiles. Despite challenges related to data quality, model interpretability, and clinical integration, continued advancements in AI technologies hold significant promise for improving lung healthcare outcomes. Overall, AI-based lung disease prediction represents a transformative step toward faster, more accurate, and more efficient respiratory disease diagnosis and management. 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

1. Introduction 

1.1Overview 

Lung Disease Prediction 

Lung diseases often progress unnoticed until advanced stages due to lack of awareness and delayed diagnosis. Traditional diagnostic methods may be time – consuming and ineffective in recognizing early indicators. This highlights the necessity for an AI–based predictive system that can enhance early detection, leading to improved patient outcomes. 

1.2 Objectives 

Lung disease prediction involves using medical data and advanced computational techniques to identify the likelihood of respiratory disorders before severe symptoms develop. With the rise of conditions such asthma, COPD, pneumonia, and lung cancer, early detection has become crucial for effective treatment and improved patient survival rates. 

Modern lung disease prediction systems typically use machine learning (ML) or deep learning (DL) models trained on clinical data such as chest X-rays, CT scans, spirometry readings, and patient health records. The goal is to assist healthcare professionals by providing timely warnings, improving diagnostic accuracy, and reducing the burden on medical systems. 

Such predictive approaches enhance preventive healthcare, support remote monitoring, and make diagnosis more accessible in low-resource settings. Overall, lung disease prediction systems play a vital role in advancing medical technology and improving public health outcomes.  

1.3 Problem Statement 

Due to delayed diagnosis and restricted access to specialised medical care, lung diseases such pneumonia, tuberculosis, COPD, and lung cancer frequently result in high morbidity and mortality, making them significant global health issues. Conventional diagnostic techniques can be laborious, prone to human error, and incapable of identifying disorders in their early stages. An effective, precise, and automated approach that can help physicians detect lung ailments early on is desperately needed given the growing amount of clinical and medical imaging data. Therefore, creating a trustworthy AI-based predictive model that can evaluate medical data, identify subtle illness patterns, and deliver timely forecasts to aid in clinical decision-making is the challenge. In respiratory healthcare, solving this issue can greatly increase early detection rates, optimize treatment plans, and improve overall patient outcomes. 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

