3. Methodology 

3.1 Architecture Overview 

To facilitate clinical decision-making, the lung disease prediction system architecture is built to effectively handle medical inputs, identify significant features, and produce precise predictions. It consists of the following essential elements: 

A. Layer of Data Acquisition 

This layer gathers unprocessed medical data, including lung sound recordings, CT scans, chest X-rays, and clinical factors (age, symptoms, medical history). Hospitals, diagnostic facilities, and publicly accessible medical datasets are possible sources of data. [1] 

B. Module for Data Preprocessing 

The raw data is cleaned and preprocessed prior to model training, including: 

Normalization, denoising, and shrinking of images 

Lung region segmentation utilizing methods like U-Net 

Extraction of features from clinical data 

Managing inconsistent or missing entries 

This guarantees consistent, high-quality data for the model. [2] 

C. Engineering and Feature Extraction 

While statistical techniques handle clinical attributes, deep learning algorithms like CNNs (Convolutional Neural Networks) automatically extract high-level features from X-ray/CT pictures. This module creates an extensive feature set that reflects the physiological, functional, and structural facets of lung health. [3] 

D. Layer of Model Development 

The fundamental deep learning and machine learning models are included in this layer, including: 

CNNs or Vision Transformers for diagnosis using images 

Hybrid models that incorporate clinical data and imagery 

Using ensemble methods to improve accuracy [4] 

The models are taught to classify lung illnesses and estimate severity levels. 

E. Engine for Prediction and Decision Support 

Probabilities or predicted classes (e.g., pneumonia, TB, COPD, normal) are produced by the trained model. 

Diagnostic insights produced by a decision-support interface include: 

Type of disease 

Confidence rating 

Heatmaps or Grad-CAM were used to highlight anomalous areas (Explainable AI). 

F. Application Layer/User Interface 

This includes a mobile or web interface that allows medical professionals to: 

Upload CT or X-ray images 

View forecasts with areas highlighted 

Obtain reports and suggestions 

Usability, clarity, and quick clinical interpretation are the objectives.[5] 

G. Database and Backend Services 

Logs, system upgrades, model outputs, and patient data are all stored on secure servers. This guarantees data confidentiality, scalability, and seamless interface with hospital systems (HIS/PACS). 

H. Ongoing Education & Model Enhancement 

The model is improved by adding fresh data from practical applications. Over time, a feedback loop improves model accuracy by enabling physicians to validate outcomes. [6] 

 

3.2 Hardware Components  

1. Data Acquisition Hardware 

Used to capture medical images and patient data. 

Digital X-Ray Machine 
For high-resolution chest X-ray image collection. 

CT Scan Machine 
Captures detailed cross-sectional lung images. 

Spirometer (optional) 
Measures lung function and supports prediction with clinical features. 

Electronic Stethoscope / Lung Sound Sensor (optional) 
For AI models that analyze lung sounds. [7] 

2. Data Storage & Management Hardware 

Stores large datasets, PACS images, and patient records. 

PACS Server (Picture Archiving and Communication System) 
Stores and retrieves X-ray/CT scans. 

Local Storage Units (NAS/SAN) 
10 TB+ recommended for handling large datasets. 

Cloud Storage (AWS, Google Cloud, Azure) 
Useful for scalable storage and remote model training. 

3. Model Training Hardware (High Performance) 

Required for deep learning model development, preprocessing, and training. 

