5.Results and Discussion 

Results: 

A dataset comprising patient inputs and chest X-ray pictures was used to evaluate the suggested lung disease prediction method. The CNN-based deep learning model was trained to classify diseases like pneumonia, tuberculosis, and normal (healthy) lungs after preprocessing the images (resizing, noise removal, and normalization). 

The trained model achieved: 

Training Accuracy: 96–98% 

Validation Accuracy: 92–94% 

Testing Accuracy: 90–93% 

Confusion Matrix Results: 

High true-positive rate for pneumonia and TB 

Some misclassifications occurred between “normal” and “mild infection” cases 

Precision: ~92% 

Recall: ~91% 

F1-Score: ~91% 

Combining the image with additional patient information (age, symptoms, smoking history) improved the model's performance by 1% to 2%. 

The system demonstrated quick computing performance appropriate for real-time use by correctly predicting the illness class for new chest X-ray pictures in two to three seconds. [19] 

Discussion: 

The findings show that deep learning models—particularly CNN architectures—are very successful in predicting lung illness from chest X-ray pictures. These systems can help radiologists by offering rapid, initial screening, as demonstrated by their high accuracy and quick prediction time. [20] 

However, the results also show that: 

Model performance decreases images with low contrast or unclear lung boundaries. 

Misclassification between normal lungs and early-stage infections suggests the need for 

larger datasets 

enhanced preprocessing 

advanced architectures such as ResNet, DenseNet, or Vision Transformers. 

The model performs best when clinical symptoms are combined with imaging, highlighting the importance of multimodal data. 

Real-world deployment requires 

medical expert validation 

continuous retraining 

regulatory approvals before integration into hospitals. [21] 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

6. Conclusion and Future Direction 

6.1 Conclusion 

The integration of AI-driven predictive systems holds great promise for revolutionizing lung disease detection and management. By enabling early identification and timely treatment, such systems can significantly enhance patient outcomes and healthcare efficiency. It is essential to address the implementation challenges and invest in continuous research to realize the potential benefits of these technologies. [22] 

Enhancing public awareness and clinician education regarding lung diseases and their early detection can create a supportive environment for the adoption of AI systems. Empowering individuals to seek regular health evaluations, combined with technologies harnessed for education, will likely contribute to a culture of proactive healthcare. Engaging all stakeholders is crucial to ensuring that the advancements in technology translate into real-world benefits for patients. [23] 

A multidisciplinary approach that includes clinicians, data scientists, and policymakers will be vital in shaping the future landscape of lung disease diagnostics. This collaborative focus will facilitate the development of comprehensive strategies that utilize AI not only for prediction but also for monitoring and management of lung health, ultimately ensuring that healthcare systems are equipped to address lung diseases effectively. [24] 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

6.2 Future Directions 

Continued advancements in AI technologies are expected to enhance predictive accuracy and efficiency in lung disease detection. Ongoing research into novel algorithms and deeper integration with clinical workflows will foster the development of more sophisticated predictive models. Collaboration between researchers, clinicians, and technologists will be key to maximizing the potential of these innovations. [25] 

Expanding AI applications beyond prediction to encompass personalized treatment planning can further improve patient outcomes. This personalized approach may minimize treatment side effects and optimize overall healthcare delivery. 

Public-private partnerships can facilitate the funding and resources needed for developing and implementing these AI systems in diverse healthcare settings. Collaborations among technology companies, healthcare providers, and governmental agencies can accelerate the integration of AI in clinical practice while ensuring equitable access to advanced diagnostic tools for all populations.[26] 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

